  "response": "While Dangal was a massive commercial success and critically acclaimed by many, some viewers found aspects of the film problematic. Here are some common criticisms leveled against it:\n\n*   **Nationalism/Jingoism:** Some critics felt the movie leaned heavily into nationalistic sentiment, portraying India as needing to prove itself on the world stage. This, they argued, overshadowed the personal story of the Phogat sisters.\n\n*   **Character portrayal of the coach:** While the film is based on a true story, the portrayal of the coach, P.R. Sondhi, was criticized as being overly negative and arguably inaccurate. He was shown as being jealous and interfering, which some felt was a distortion of reality for dramatic effect.\n\n*   **Mahavir Phogat's character:** Some viewers found Mahavir Phogat's character to be overly controlling and authoritarian. His methods of training were seen as bordering on abusive, and his relentless pressure on his daughters was viewed as detrimental to their personal well-being.\n\n*   **Formulaic Bollywood tropes:** Despite its unique subject matter, some argued that Dangal fell into predictable Bollywood patterns, including the underdog story, the emotional family drama, and the triumphant climax. This made the film feel somewhat predictable and less groundbreaking than it could have been.\n\nIt's important to note that these are just some common criticisms and that not everyone shares these opinions. Many people found the movie to be inspiring, well-made, and a powerful story of female empowerment.",
